    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/nagaraja-cou1-force-at-40mm-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Force at 40 mm displacement QoI comparison — FEA vs. experimental (N=11, two laboratories)",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/nagaraja-f1717-bench-n11-lab2",
      "description": "The FEA ensemble (three independent analyst teams: FDA CDRH, Ansys Inc., DePuy Synthes) predicted force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending loading. Experimental data were collected across two independent laboratories (Lab A: University of Memphis Biomechanics Lab; Lab B: DePuy Synthes internal test facility) using eleven physical constructs per laboratory, with polyurethane foam blocks (Sawbones 20 pcf) as the bone surrogate. All three FEA predictions fell within the pre-established ±10% acceptance window relative to the mean experimental value, and the normalised validation metric E/uval remained below the 1.96 threshold for all QoIs. The inter-laboratory variability in the experimental reference data was characterised using a two-sample F-test; no statistically significant difference between laboratory means was identified (p = 0.43). Analyst-to-analyst variability across the three FEA teams was likewise within 4.2% for this QoI, confirming robustness of the modeling framework to user interpretation of boundary conditions. Material properties were drawn from ISO 5832-1 coupon data supplied by the implant manufacturer and independently verified by one analyst team using nanoindentation. Contact interactions at the screw–rod interface were modelled as frictional (μ = 0.2, Coulomb) in all three FEA submissions, consistent with the experimentally measured interface condition. The detailed post-processing workflow, solver settings, and analyst team identifiers are documented in the companion technical report TR-NAG-2024-CB-003."
    }
  ],
