      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark problems with known analytical solutions must be reproduced within 1% for linear elastic beam bending and contact patch problems.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA platforms have been benchmarked against Timoshenko beam theory (cantilever, point load) and Hertzian contact analytical solutions. Errors were below 0.6% in all cases. Documentation is included in the respective software qualification records referenced in TR-NAG-2024-CB-003."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate that QoI changes less than 5% upon uniform mesh refinement.",
      "rationale": "A structured mesh convergence study was performed by the FDA analyst team using three mesh densities (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). The Richardson extrapolation-based grid convergence index (GCI) for construct stiffness was 1.3%, and for force at 40 mm displacement was 1.8%. The medium mesh was selected as the production mesh, achieving Gradation 3 (formal GCI quantification). Required level is Gradation 2; factor exceeds requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge to below 1e-6 for all load steps; time-stepping sensitivity must be demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "All FEA submissions used implicit quasi-static solvers with automatic time-stepping. Force residuals converged to below 1e-7 in all load increments. A time-step sensitivity check (halving the maximum increment size) produced less than 0.3% change in all QoIs. Gradation 2 is achieved and matches the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup (boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions) must be performed by a second analyst not involved in model construction.",
      "rationale": "Each of the three FEA submissions underwent peer review by an independent analyst within the same organisation. Boundary condition interpretation was documented in a standardised checklist aligned with ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. No material assignment or contact definition errors were identified during review. Gradation 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model must capture the dominant physical mechanisms (elastoplastic screw behaviour, foam crushable behaviour) with documented justification for simplifications.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA teams employed bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity for the titanium alloy screw (Ti-6Al-4V, ISO 5832-3) and a crushable foam model for the polyurethane bone surrogate. Geometric nonlinearity was enabled in all analyses to capture large-displacement effects at 40 mm displacement. Model form choices are justified against published material characterisation data and prior FDA CDRH modelling guidance. Gradation 3 is achieved and matches the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material property inputs must be traceable to measured coupon data from the same material lot used in the physical constructs; geometric inputs must be derived from calibrated CMM measurements.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy elastic modulus (E = 114 GPa) and yield stress (σy = 880 MPa) were obtained from ISO 5832-3 coupon testing of the same material lot as the implants. Foam modulus and plateau stress were characterised from compression testing of the same Sawbones batch. Screw geometry was derived from CMM measurements (±0.01 mm tolerance). All inputs are documented in TR-NAG-2024-CB-003 Appendix B. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 physical constructs tested; constructs must be from production-representative implant lots with documented dimensional inspection.",
      "rationale": "Eleven physical constructs were tested per laboratory (N=11 total per site, N=22 overall). Implants were drawn from two production lots with dimensional inspection confirming conformance to drawing tolerances. Polyurethane foam blocks were from a single Sawbones lot to minimise inter-specimen variability. Gradation 3 is achieved and matches the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing must be performed under at least two distinct loading configurations or environmental conditions to assess model sensitivity.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration only. No axial compression-only or torsion conditions were included in this validation campaign. This limits the achieved level to Gradation 2, which is below the required Gradation 3. This gap is acknowledged and documented as an accepted limitation given that the COU is explicitly scoped to compression-bending only and the decision consequence is Medium rather than High."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) must be demonstrably equivalent to the as-tested experimental conditions, with quantified differences documented.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared comparing FEA inputs to experimentally measured values for all significant model inputs. Maximum deviation between FEA geometry and CMM-measured implant geometry was 0.8%. Foam material properties used in FEA were within 3% of batch-measured values. Boundary condition equivalency was confirmed by comparing fixture compliance measurements to the rigid fixture assumption in FEA (fixture compliance accounted for <0.5% of total displacement). Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) must be computed for all QoIs; acceptance threshold E/uval < 1.96 must be met.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for all three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) following the ASME V&V 40 framework. Values were: stiffness E/uval = 0.87; yield force E/uval = 1.12; force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.34. All three are below the 1.96 threshold. Additionally, all three FEA ensemble predictions fell within ±10% of the experimental mean. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must be directly linked to the COU decision (construct structural integrity under compression-bending) and must be clinically or regulatorily meaningful.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and are the quantities used by FDA reviewers to assess spinal implant structural adequacy. They are directly linked to the COU decision to accept the FEA modeling framework for predicting compression-bending performance. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
